      "role": "user",
      "content": "can u explain that \"spooky action at a distance\" part a bit more? like why did einstein call it spooky? what makes it feel so weird compared to just, i dont know, two coins always landing on heads together?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seemed to violate his belief in local realism, which is the idea that objects are only influenced by their immediate surroundings and that information cannot travel faster than the speed of light. When he first heard about quantum entanglement, he couldn't reconcile it with the principles of classical physics, which is why he described it as \"spooky.\" This term reflects the strange and non-intuitive nature of entanglement, where two particles remain connected and instantly affect each other no matter how far apart they are, seemingly defying the speed limit of the universe. This goes beyond just two coins always landing on heads together; entanglement suggests a deeper, instantaneous link that challenges our everyday understanding of how the world works. It's like having a pair of magical dice that always land on the same number, but without a physical connection, implying some mysterious force at play.",
      "source": "target",
